Problem Statement: 1 page

People (Students, staff, and visitors) who need to find classrooms, offices, labs, restrooms, or events inside Patrick F. Taylor Hall (PFT) often experience confusion 
and delays during indoor navigation, even when they try to rely on room numbers, signage, maps, or their phones. Common breakdowns happen around unclear room-numbering 
patterns, insufficient or hard-to-interpret directional signage, similar-looking hallways that reduce orientation, and difficult floor transitions (stairs/elevators). 
These problems can be very annoying when people are short on time or trying to find easy ways to get around, like lifts, ramps and automatic doors. So, a lot of people 
use ad-hoc coping strategies like asking others for help, which might not be reliable or easy. This formative study investigates these real navigation pain points, the 
cues people actually use, and barriers to adoption in order to derive user needs and design requirements for a usable digital indoor navigation system for PFT.


